                        <p> <hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE 124.—<name type="person">Private J. F. Dean</name>, <name type="organization">Co. I, 43d N. C.</name>;
                                admitted <date type="admit" when="1963-12-11">Dec. 11, 1863</date>.  Died <date type="death" when="1864-01-01">Jan. 1, 1864</date>.   <hi rend="italic">Post-mortem</hi> examination: The larynx and trachea were of a pale greenish-blue
                                        color but otherwise normal. Both lungs were inflamed; the
                                        first lobe of the right lung was hepatized red and gray and
                                        had at its base, posteriorly, a large abscess the size of a
                                        teacup filled with offensive pus and broken-down pulmonary
                                        tissue; the second lobe was splenified; the third in the
                                        last stage of red hepatization. The liver was very large and
                                        presented whitish lardaceous spots; the spleen was flabby;
                                        the kidneys congested.—<hi rend="italic"><name type="person" key="245">Ass't Surgeon Harrison Allen</name>, <name type="organization" key="190">U. S. A.</name>, <name type="hospital" key="176">Lincoln Hospital</name>, Washington, D. C.</hi> </p>                        
